[[File:More.JPG|thumb|''Morė'', ready for burning]]
'''Morė''' is one of the main attributes of the traditional Lithuanian folk festival ''[[Užgavėnės]]''. It is an artificial woman (''čiūčiala''), stuffed with various materials, who is ultimately burned in a [[bonfire]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vaiškūnas|first1=Jonas|title=Ką iš tikrųjų įkūnija Užgavėnių Morė?|url=https://www.delfi.lt/grynas/gyvenimas/jvaiskunas-ka-is-tikruju-ikunija-uzgaveniu-more.d?id=55756613|website=DELFI.lt|accessdate=21 February 2012|language=lt}}</ref>
She is associated with the winter personification as a Slavic goddess [[Marzanna]]. She is burned because once it was believed that it will help to bring spring faster.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laurinkienė|first1=Nijolė|title=Kas toji Užgavėnių Morė?|date=2012|url=http://tautosmenta.lt/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Laurinkiene_Nijole/Laurinkiene_LK_2012_1.pdf|accessdate=28 March 2018|language=lt}}</ref> Participants of the ritual are dancing around the bonfire and shouting "Žiema, žiema, bėk iš kiemo" (Winter, winter, run from the yard).<ref>{{cite web|title=Žiema, žiema, bėk iš kiemo - LRT|url=http://www.lrt.lt/mediateka/irasas/7588/ziema-ziema-bek-is-kiemo|website=[[Lietuvos Radijas ir Televizija]]|accessdate=28 March 2018|language=lt}}</ref>
